solutions.content:
We use the sliding window approach, where the current window is `[j, i)`.

There are two additional pointers (`p1` and `p2`) to track the elements equeal to `minK` and `maxK`.

#### Catch-Up

First, we find subarrays `[j, i)` where all elements are within the limits.

Then, for each `j`, we track two closest positions `p1` (minK) and `p2` (maxK) greater than `j`.

The number of subarrays for each `j` is `i - max(p1, p2)`. This is how it works for this test case:

```
[5,2,1,2,3,2,1,2,5]
1
3
```

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/b7f3255a-3129-4fcc-aba0-67c1aea12245_1665966157.317106.png)

**C++**
```cpp
long long countSubarrays(vector<int>& nums, int minK, int maxK) {
    long long res = 0, n = nums.size();
    for (int i = 0, j = 0; i <= n; ++i)
        if (i == n || nums[i] < minK || nums[i] > maxK)
            for (int p1 = j, p2 = j; j <= i; ++j) {
                while (p1 < i && (p1 < j || nums[p1] != minK))
                    ++p1;
                while (p2 < i && (p2 < j || nums[p2] != maxK))
                    ++p2;
                res += i - max(p1, p2);
            }
    return res;
}
```

#### Extend
The logic can be simplified if we track subarrays on the left. The number of subarrays for each `i` would be`min(p1, p2) - j`.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/ed9cfc10-02d9-4329-8bc2-f79d0cc391cc_1665966478.258106.png)

**C++**
```cpp
long long countSubarrays(vector<int>& nums, int minK, int maxK) {
    long long res = 0, n = nums.size();
    for (int i = 0, j = -1, p1 = -1, p2 = -1; i < n; ++i) {
        if (nums[i] < minK || nums[i] > maxK)
            p1 = p2 = j = i;
        p1 = nums[i] == minK ? i : p1;
        p2 = nums[i] == maxK ? i : p2;
        res += min(p1, p2) - j;
    }
    return res;
}
```

