# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->We have to find the subarray having minK and maxK as greatest and lowest bound. We have to keep track at each iteration about the existance of minK and maxK and simultaneously we have to count the subarrays. 

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. First of all, declare bool variables like minFound and maxFound to keep the track of minK and maxK in subarray.
2. Declare integer variables-
- start variable to store the starting index of subarray.
- minStart variable to store the minimum start index of subarray.
- maxStart variable to store the maxmum start index of subarray.
3. In each iteration,
 - If nums[i] is smaller mink or greater than maxK, set minFound and maxfound to false and set start = i+1;
 - if nums[i] is equal minK, set minFound to true and minStart = i.
 - if nums[i] is equal maxK, set maxFound to true and maxStart = i.
4. In each iteration, we have to calculate total number of subarrays,
- for that, we have to find the minimum of minStart and maxstart because in array maxK can occur before minK as array isnt sorted.
- we have to subtract the minimum of minStart and maxStart with start variable because start is the initial of subarray.

# Example With Dry Run
