solutions.content:
# Solution/Intuition

## Finding Segments

First, lets make some observations about good (what we will call "fixed-bounded" arrays) subarrays:
-They must contain minK and maxK **at least once**
-No elements can lie outside of the range **$$[minK, maxK]$$**


The second observation allows us to split the array into portions we can more easily calculate the sums with: Say that any element lies outside of the good range. Obviously, that element cannot be in any good subarray we will count towards the answer. Therefore, we may assume that there exists no good subarray from a[l] to a[r] such that l < i < r; **any good subarray will lie either completely to the left of or completely to the right of a bad element** (outside of the range $$[minK, maxK]$$). 

We will calculate the answer between each pair of adjacent bad elements separately, and increment our final answer. (For the sake of our implemntation, assume the indexies -1 and n (0 based) are bad). 

## Computing For Each Segment

For each segment, we know that all elements lie between [minK, maxK]. Notice the positioning of maxK, minK in any subarray of a subsegment does not matter: 

[1, 2, 3], [3, 1, 1, 1, 1, 2], [2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 3, 1], [2, 1, 3, 2]. 
(when minK = 1, maxK = 3, all the above subarrays are good)

Therefore, to calculate the number of good subarrays in a segment, we simply need to fix the rightmost index (we will call j) in the subarray, and calculate for how many indexes (i) to the left such that the subarray is good. (Can be the opposite too)

Conveniently, we notice that **if the subarray starting from l ending at r is good, the subarray starting from l-1 is also good (as long as it lies within the segment)**. This works going rightwards too, but we have fixed r in order to avoid overcounting. All we have to do now is find the lastmost l such that the subarray from l to r is good, and increment the answer by (l - SegmentLeftbound + 1). 

Now, all we require for a subarray to be good is for it to contain minK and maxK. We can simply store the positions of their occurances, and find the greatest position of both minK and maxK such that it is not greater than r. The minimum of their positions marks the maximum l such that a[l:r] is a good subarray. We will use binary search to find their positions in O($$logN$$). 

See code for implementation along with some things you should be careful with. 

---
There is a more efficient (and possibly more elegant?) O($$N$$) solution using 2 pointers, so try it out if you want a challenge!

But our O($$NlogN$$) binary search for each index passes the time constraints perfectly, and avoids any tedious casework. 


# Complexity
O($$NlogN$$) - O($$N$$) for each element, logN for binary searching at each index 

# Implementation 
```cpp
typedef long long ll; 

class Solution {
public:
    long long countSubarrays(vector<int>& a, int lk, int rk) {
        ll n = a.size(); 
        ll ans = 0;

        //find position of bad indicies 
        vector<int> bads(1, -1); 

        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            p[i+1] += p[i];
            if (lk > a[i] || rk < a[i]) {
                p[i]++; 
                bads.push_back(i);
            }
        }
        bads.push_back(n); 


        for (int i = 0; i < bads.size()-1; ++i) {
            //the subarray from l to r is good. 
            //interestingly, l > r may occur, but the following loop 
            //will not run, and therefore we will continue
            int l = bads[i]+1, r = bads[i+1]-1; 

            //stores the positions of minK and maxK
            vector<int> mns, mxs; 

            for (int j = l; j <= r; ++j) {
                if (a[j] == lk) {
                    mns.push_back(j); 
                } if (a[j] == rk) {
                    mxs.push_back(j); 
                }
            }

            //if minK or maxK does not exist, we can continue to the next segment
            if (min(mns.size(), mxs.size()) == 0) continue; 

            for (int j = l; j <= r; ++j) {
                //if the minimum index does not lie before j we may continue
                if (mns[0] > j || mxs[0] > j) continue; 

                //lowest index to go to 
                int low = 1e9; 

                //find last minK using binary search
                int lo = 0, hi = mns.size()-1; 
                while (lo < hi) {
                    int mid = lo + (hi - lo + 1)/2;
                    if (mns[mid] <= j) lo = mid;
                    else hi = mid - 1; 
                }
                low = min(low, mns[lo]); 

                //find last maxK using binary search
