solutions.content:
# Intuition
If `minK = 5`, `maxK = 11`, `nums = [6, 6, 6, 6, 6, 6, 5, 6, 6, 6, 10, 11, 7, 8]`,
how many *fixed-bound subarrays* can be formed?

First, we know that the subarray `5, 6, 6, 6, 10, 11` must to be a part of the *fixed-bound subarray*.

Second, we are able to count the number of the **bolded** part of `[`**6, 6, 6, 6, 6, 6,**`5, 6, 6, 6, 10, 11, ...]` as the *fixed-bound subarray*.
The number of the bolded part can be form as the *fixed-bound subarray* is `(index of the last '6' = 5) - (index of the first '6' = 0) + 1` = 6 (not included `5, 6, 6, 6, 10, 11` itself).

> The rest parts will be explained in Approach

To conclude our intuition,
if we iterate the `nums`, we care about
1. if `nums[i]` lies in the closed interval `[minK, maxK]`, we mark `i` as the first (furthest) `validIndex` so far.
:: Notice that the `validIndex` of our example is `0` (the index of the first `'6'`)
2. once we successfully find both `minK` and `maxK`, we can calculate the number of *fixed-bound subarray* that can be formed.
For `[`**6, 6, 6, 6, 6, 6,**`5, 6, 6, 6, 10, 11, ...]`, we can form `min(indexOf(5), indexOf(11)) - validIndex + 1` = 7 subarrays (included `5, 6, 6, 6, 10, 11` itself).
:: Notice that the general formula should be `min(indexOf(minK), indexOf(maxK)) - validIndex + 1`
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
But how about if we meet a valid `nums[i]` after `[minK, maxK]`?
To continue the above case, `[6, 6, 6, 6, 6, 6, 5, 6, 6, 6, 10, 11,`**7, 8**`]`.

Simply to start with, how many subarrays can be formed if we include a new `'7'` only?
The answer is still `min(indexOf(5), indexOf(11)) - validIndex + 1` = 7 subarrays.
Because we are just adding a new valid number `'7'` into the *fixed-bound subarrays* that we have.

If adding a `'8'`? `'8'` is also a valid number in range `[minK, maxK]`.
The answer is still `min(indexOf(5), indexOf(11)) - validIndex + 1` = 7 subarrays.
It is the same reason as above, and this time we are adding the new `'8'` after the `'7'` to those *fixed-bound subarrays*.

Finally, in case we meet a `nums[i]` that lies outside of `[minK, maxK]`, we have to reinitialize the records of `validIndex`, `found[]` and `lastIndex[]`.
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Too Long; Didn't Read
- find `validIndex` such that `nums[validIndex]` lies in range `[minK, maxK]`
  - keep `validIndex` as left biased as possible
- if found `minK` at `i`, set `found[minK] = true` and update `lastIndex[minK] = i`.
- if found `maxK` at `i`, set `found[maxK] = true` and update `lastIndex[maxK] = i`.
- if found both `minK` and `maxK`, accumulate the `result`
- if met any `nums[i]` that out of range `[minK, maxK]`, reinitialize the variables.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
**Solution 1**
```
class Solution {
public:
  long long countSubarrays(vector<int>& nums, int minK, int maxK) {
    // index 0->min 1->max
    int found[2] {}, lastIndex[2] = {}, validIndex = -1;
    long result = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
      if (nums[i] < minK or nums[i] > maxK) {
        found[0] = found[1] = false;
        validIndex = -1;
        continue;
      }
      if (validIndex == -1 and minK <= nums[i] and nums[i] <= maxK)
        validIndex = i;
      if (nums[i] == minK) {
        found[0] = true;
        lastIndex[0] = i;
      }
      if (nums[i] == maxK) {
        found[1] = true;
        lastIndex[1] = i;
      }
      if (found[0] and found[1]) {
        result += min(lastIndex[0], lastIndex[1]) - validIndex + 1;
      }
    }

    return result;
  }
};
```

