When TreeSet can make your life easier and OJ is ok with O(n log n), why not?

# High-Level Explanation:

We follow Napoleon's strategy: Divide and Conquer, just to be dramatic.

We divide the array into chunks of the biggest fixed-bound subarrays. Then for each of them, we count the number of fixed-bound subarrays.


````   

    TreeSet<Integer> minIndexTreeSet = new TreeSet<>();
    TreeSet<Integer> maxIndexTreeSet = new TreeSet<>();
    int minK, maxK;
    long sum = 0;
    int[] nums;

    public long countSubarrays(int[] nums, int minK, int maxK) {
        int start = 0;
        int size = nums.length;
        this.nums = nums;
        this.minK = minK;
        this.maxK = maxK;
        for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
            int num = nums[i];
            if (num < minK || num > maxK) {
                add(start, i - 1);
                start = i + 1;
                minIndexTreeSet.clear();
                maxIndexTreeSet.clear();
            }
            if (num == minK) {
                minIndexTreeSet.add(i);
            }
            if (num == maxK) {
                maxIndexTreeSet.add(i);
            }
        }
        add(start, size - 1);
        return sum;
    }

    private void add(int start, int end) {
        if (start > end || maxIndexTreeSet.size() == 0 || minIndexTreeSet.size() == 0)
            return;

        for (int i = start; i <= end; i++) {
            Integer floorMinIndex = minIndexTreeSet.floor(i);
            if (floorMinIndex == null) {
                continue;
            }
            Integer floorMaxIndex = maxIndexTreeSet.floor(i);
            if (floorMaxIndex == null) {
                continue;
            }
            int smallerIndex = Math.min(floorMinIndex, floorMaxIndex);
            int dif = smallerIndex - start + 1;
            sum += dif;
        }
    }

